			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">First of all, Sehra brought up the issue that shamans should look at being able to hold agro as a <span style="text-decoration: underline">strength</span>.  Not as a <span style="text-decoration: underline">balance </span>to the <span style="font-style: italic">overwhelming </span>power of their dots  <img src="images/smiles/icon_rolleyes.gif" alt="Rolling Eyes" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
Secondly, shaman dots are nowhere near as powerful as necros.  Necros get lines of dots in more damage types that shamans - shamans only have disease and poison-based dots.  When you're fighting in PoD or Veksar, for example, shaman dots are useless.  I understand, that's a limitation of many classes.  But necros have dots that work in virtually every environment.  Necros also have significantly higher mana pools and unrivaled mana regen.  As I said before, shaman mana regen is active, just like pet canni.  While they're casting cannibalize/using canni AA and then casting stoicism/torpor/quiessence, they're not accomplishing anything else.  Mages, of all other classes, should be able to understand this, since it so closely approximates the active mana regen of pet canni.
<br />

<br />
Third, when someone points to the shaman dots as superb dps potential, and I point out that they can't actually be <span style="text-decoration: underline">used </span>to generate that dps without resulting in a dead shaman, why does that make me a druid?  People who make that claim simply haven't played a shaman, or they'd know that you can't pile on dot after dot without getting agro and dying.  All those dots look nice on Lucy's, but try stacking 3 of them in the game and see what happens.  Even with a good tank, you'll pull agro.  And that's never in the best interests of the group.  Shamans aren't tanks.
<br />

<br />
Theoretical dps and realistic dps are two entirely different things.  The agro from casting a dot that causes 1800 damage over 6 ticks is higher than the agro from a wizard crit causing three times as much damage.  That's why shamans are upset - their dots have <span style="font-style: italic">artificial </span>agro counters (disease or poison) built in, to offset the overpowering nature of dots  <img src="images/smiles/icon_rolleyes.gif" alt="Rolling Eyes" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
Fourth, whoever said anything about being able to nuke as well as druids?  Shamans are looking for a decent nuke, even one with a craptastic mana ratio, so they have something to do during raids.  
<br />

<br />
Fifth, how do you figure shamans are THE buff class?  People seem to forget that stat buffs are almost completely useless except to power-level your twink.  This petition is about the end-game raid shaman.  At that level, everyone's stats are maxed.  Enchanter haste is far superior.  Both cleric and (I believe) druids have better hp buffs.  We get no mana regen buffs (cannibalize is obviously self-only).  How do you figure shamans are THE buff class?  We can buff your charisma and agility?
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Maybe</span>, if they introduce some sort of endurance-regen spell, like KEI for melees, you could once again consider shamans as buff kings.  There's talk of an AA skill in GoD that would do that very thing.  But as things stand, enchanters, clerics, and druids are all better overall buff classes than shamans.  Stat buffs are <span style="text-decoration: underline">useless</span>.  Outside of the attack increase from FA, shaman buffs aren't too hot.  
<br />

<br />
Finally, if you think a componentless-FA with a longer duration is overpowering, how do you feel about 4-hour KEI with no component costs?  
<br />

<br />
Whisp</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
