			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">[quote="samxp"]</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Whisp wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">That's why shamans are upset - their dots have artificial agro counters (disease or poison) built in,<span style="font-weight: bold"> to offset the overpowering nature of dots</span></td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
That pretty much explainned why to you. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I was being facetious.  
<br />

<br />
Take a shaman casting a DOT that will, over its full course of 2.1 minutes, do 1500 damage.  Simultaneously, take a mage or wizard casting a nuke that will immediately do 1500 damage, and has the potential to crit.  See which character gets agro.  That's the big complaint about dots - they have artificial agro built-in.  They can't crit like nukes (until the release of critical-dot AAs in GoD), but create more agro than a nuke of equivalent damage.  
<br />

<br />
My comments about enchanter haste being superior are based on how enchanters get better haste at a particular level than shamans, and (if I recall - could be wrong here) that their haste buff lasts longer.  Enchanters are better at haste, which is a buff.
<br />

<br />
Shamans are well-rounded.  They can do a lot of things.  Shamans can heal - just not as good as a cleric or a druid.  Shamans can buff hitpoints, but clerics and druids are generally better.  Their one big stat buff, FA, is really only in demand because of the attack boost, stats being generally capped at end-game and largely useless anyway.  But beastlords can buff attack ratings even higher.  Shamans can haste, but enchanters are better.  Shamans can even tank, in the right situations, if necessary.  But, obviously, there are many other classes that make better tanks.  Shamans have pets, but they're pretty lousy compared to magicians, necros, and beastlords.  
<br />

<br />
They make great exp-group partners, because they can do a lot of things and fill a lot of roles in a 6-person group.  They wouldn't be your first choice for any of the above roles, but they can server as any of them.
<br />

<br />
Shamans can really do two things very well; slow and debuff mobs.  They have the best slow in the game, by a whopping 5% over beastlords.  They also have the best combo of resist debuffs and melee debuffs.  In every other major facet of game mechanics, they are second-rate.  They excel at slowing and debuffing.  
<br />

<br />
And there's the rub.  Those skills don't stack on raids.  When you're raiding big targets, you don't need more than a couple shamans.  Debuff the target with malos, and then slow the target.  One or two shamans can handle that.  As with other well-rounded classes, like druids and arguably necros, they are versatile and valuable in 6-person groups, but not terribly useful in raids.  Maybe nothing can be done about it - I don't know.
<br />

<br />
Oh well, I can see we're not going to agree about this issue in full.  I would encourage you all to read the shaman proposal on shaman crucible, and some of the relevant posts.  
<br />

<br />
Let me reiterate: I'm NOT bashing mages.  I play a mage.  At this point, my main character is a mage.  I haven't played my level 59 shaman in months, literally not one time.  I enjoy the mage much more.  I just wanted to defend the viewpoint of shamans, who (in my opinion) were being unfairly compared to "droods" and being portrayed as whiners.
<br />

<br />
Whisp</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
